{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl1440\margr1440\pgnstart27\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts27\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\qr MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\qr     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \chpgn \par }\pard\qj \plain\f8\fs20 CHR$ -Function--Character\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab CHR$\par \par \par \par \par Format\par CHR$(character-code)\par \par Type\par String\par \par Cross Reference\par ASC\par \par Description\par The CHR$ function returns the character corresponding to the ASCII character code specified by the value of the character-code.\par \par CHR$ is the inverse of the ASC function.\par \par Character-code is a numeric-expression with a value from 0 to 32767 inclusive, specifying the number of the character you wish to use. If the value of character-code is greater than 255, it is repeatedly reduced by 256 until it is less than 256. If the value of the character-code is not an integer, it is rounded to the nearest integer.\par \par Examples\par \par 100 PRINT CHR$(72)\par Prints H.\par \par 100 X$=CHR$(33)\par Sets X$ equal to !.\par \par Program for a complete listing of all ASCII characters and their corresponding ASCII values, run the following program.\par \par 100 CALL CLEAR\par 110 IMAGE ### ## ### ##\par 120 FOR A=32 TO 127\par 130 PRINT USING 110:A,CHR$(A);\par 140 NEXT A\par \par \par \par \par \par }
